d. In the course of a generation, the community of Shklov-the most prominent of the towns in the area-witnessed an explosion of intellectual and cultural activity. Focusing on the social and intellectual odysseys of merchants, maskilim, and rabbis, and their varied attempts to combine Judaism and European culture, David Fishman here chronicles the remarkable story of these first modern Jews of Russia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHaskalahzBelaruszShkloŭxHistoryy18th century. 0aJewszBelaruszShkloŭxIntellectual life. 0aShkloŭ (Belarus)xIntellectual life. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh1 aFishman, David E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFunabashi, Yoichi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081472614340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814728864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814728864/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK